 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">To quantify and test multiple predictors of now/human responses to the climate question, 
  <span class="bold">
   <a rid="pone.0138208.t002" ref-type="table" href="#pone.0138208.t002">Table 2</a>
  </span>estimates five weighted logistic regression models. Such models are commonly employed with the categorical dependent variables of survey data. If 
  <span class="italic">P</span>(
  <span class="italic">y</span>
  <sub>
   <span class="italic">i</span>
  </sub> = 1) is the conditional probability of a now/human response by the 
  <span class="italic">i</span>th individual, the odds of such a response are defined as 
  <span class="italic">O</span>(
  <span class="italic">y</span>
  <sub>
   <span class="italic">i</span>
  </sub> = 1) = 
  <span class="italic">P</span>(
  <span class="italic">y</span>
  <sub>
   <span class="italic">i</span>
  </sub> = 1)/
  <span class="italic">P</span>(
  <span class="italic">y</span>
  <sub>
   <span class="italic">i</span>
  </sub> ≠1). Logistic regression models the conditional log odds as a linear function of 
  <span class="italic">m</span> predictor variables 
  <span class="italic">x</span>
  <sub>1
   <span class="italic">i</span>
  </sub>, 
  <span class="italic">x</span>
  <sub>2
   <span class="italic">i</span>
  </sub>, …, 
  <span class="italic">x</span>
  <sub>m
   <span class="italic">i</span>
  </sub>: 
